{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509960"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:22:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:22:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11466"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11466"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.06,0.07,0.18,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4098"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111897"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4098"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11466"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93961"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4938"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5502"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111897"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA general practitioner is reviewing a patient with stage 4 lung cancer who presents with progressively worsening fatigue. This patient is known to the community palliative care team and recent investigations were at baseline levels. The patient\u0027s family wants to know how to improve energy levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for the patient\u0027s fatigue?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Advise prolonged bedrest","Dexamphetamine","Modafinil","Low dose dexamethasone","Supportive measures"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupportive measures\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. Fatigue is a common symptom in end-stage diseases, and is often related to disease progression. Supportive measures include patient education, exercise, dietary advice, psychosocial support and involvement of allied health where necessary. It is important to understand how the fatigue is impacting the patient and their family, and to engage them in understanding and managing their fatigue in order to maximise their quality of life. Satisfactory symptomatic treatment however, can be difficult. Fatigue may also be\u00a0a consequence of reversible causes secondary to primary disease, for example anaemia requiring blood transfusion. In this question, there is no suggestion of a treatable underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvise prolonged bedrest\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because rest alone does not reverse fatigue in greatly progressed disease. Unnecessary decrease in activity may lead to increased weakness and reduced quality of sleep, exacerbating fatigue. Conversely, encouraging exercise has been associated with improved mood and energy levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no consistent evidence supporting the use of psychostimulants to reduce fatigue in a palliative setting - for this reason, \u003Cstrong\u003Edexamphetamine \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E modafinil\u003C/strong\u003E are less appropriate options for managing this patient\u0027s fatigue. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow dose dexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E may have a role in reducing fatigue in the palliative care setting, but it should only be considered once supportive measures has been initiated and any potentially reversible causes addressed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Management of fatigue in palliative care focuses on supportive measures to educate patients and empower them to improve symptom control.","There is limited evidence for use of corticosteroids n improving cancer related fatigue, even less for psychostimulants such as dexamphetamine and modafinil."],"references":["eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne (AU): Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd; 2021. Fatigue in palliative care [updated 2016 Jul; cited 2022 Feb 17].","Klasson C, Helde Frankling M, Lundh Hagelin C, Bj\u00f6rkhem-Bergman L. Fatigue in Cancer Patients in Palliative Care\u2014A Review on Pharmacological Interventions. Cancers. 2021; 13(5):985. https://doi.org/10.3390/cancers13050985"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93961"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11466"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93961"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-20T18:31:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-20T18:31:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4098"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111897"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com